# Build outputs are generated from CMake and should not be committed.
# Upstream: developers run CMake or Visual Studio locally.
# Downstream: source-only checkouts rebuild these folders when needed.
build/
cmake-build-*/
out/

# Visual Studio and editor folders are machine-local state.
# Upstream: IDEs create these folders during local development.
# Downstream: repository users should keep their own local settings.
.vs/
.vscode/
.idea/

# Compiled binaries and intermediate objects are generated artifacts.
# Upstream: the compiler and linker create these files.
# Downstream: the repository stores source files instead of build products.
*.exe
*.dll
*.lib
*.obj
*.pdb
*.ilk
*.exp

# CMake generated files are tied to one local build directory.
# Upstream: CMake creates them during configuration.
# Downstream: each developer regenerates them for their own environment.
CMakeCache.txt
CMakeFiles/
cmake_install.cmake
Makefile

# Temporary logs are local diagnostics.
# Upstream: tools and manual runs may create them.
# Downstream: committed source should not depend on them.
*.log

# Office lock files are temporary and can break collaboration if committed.
# Upstream: Word or PowerPoint creates these files while a document is open.
# Downstream: the repository keeps the real documents, not editor locks.
~$*.docx
~$*.pptx
